00:20:37,352 --> 00:20:39,115
Sickness is motive.

260
00:20:39,254 --> 00:20:40,448
Look sharp.

261
00:20:40,756 --> 00:20:42,348
The coroner's prelim on the Ruski.

262
00:20:42,424 --> 00:20:45,518
Isn't that the wacko poison
that Reese used on them Arab kids?

263
00:20:50,432 --> 00:20:51,922
Tiff...

264
00:20:52,100 --> 00:20:55,866
You like riddles?
You know, puzzles and shit? Brainteasers?

265
00:20:55,938 --> 00:20:57,565
Sure, only if I do the teasing.

266
00:20:58,106 --> 00:21:02,270
Why is there a space
between Lyons and Spakowsky?

267
00:21:02,911 --> 00:21:05,175
What does that even mean? Come on!

268
00:21:05,247 --> 00:21:07,044
We had a Spakowsky in my rookie year.

269
00:21:07,115 --> 00:21:08,446
South precinct.

270
00:21:09,851 --> 00:21:10,943
Come again?

271
00:21:11,086 --> 00:21:13,384
Not your Spakowsky. This guy's a cop.

272
00:21:13,588 --> 00:21:14,885
Keep talking.

273
00:21:15,190 --> 00:21:16,953
Guy's a fucking asshole.

274
00:21:17,125 --> 00:21:20,288
He's the King Kong of assholes.
He's a fucking legend.

275
00:21:20,963 --> 00:21:22,453
His name's up on a wall.

276
00:21:26,802 --> 00:21:27,791
What?

277
00:21:30,706 --> 00:21:33,869
Some chief in the '30s
thought it would boost morale.

278
00:21:34,309 --> 00:21:38,507
They kept it up till '81 or '82,
and it got to be like a booby prize.

279
00:21:38,814 --> 00:21:40,645
It was downtown in the lobby...

280
00:21:40,716 --> 00:21:43,879
...till they remodeled.
Must've passed it by 1,000 times.

281
00:21:43,986 --> 00:21:47,649
I guess I need to open my eyes
and look around sometime.

282
00:21:47,889 --> 00:21:51,052
Lyons, I don't remember,
but Spakowsky was around.

283
00:21:51,393 --> 00:21:55,056
This guy was so fucking mean
his wife shot him in the foot.

284
00:21:55,230 --> 00:21:56,595
Who was '65?

285
00:21:56,765 --> 00:21:58,164
Who was in that space?

286
00:21:58,233 --> 00:21:59,996
You got me, bud. I don't know.

287
00:22:01,036 --> 00:22:04,836
You're saying they took a name off?
Why would they do that?

288
00:22:05,007 --> 00:22:09,000
I don't know. I called Records.
They say they don't know who it was...

289
00:22:09,177 --> 00:22:11,008
...and don't know why it's not there.

290
00:22:11,847 --> 00:22:13,576
We better find out.

291
00:23:09,404 --> 00:23:11,964
Lieutenant, just the man I wanted to see.

292
00:23:15,911 --> 00:23:17,071
"Robert Milano."

293
00:23:17,145 --> 00:23:18,339
That's right.

294
00:23:19,247 --> 00:23:21,147
Cop of the Year, 1965.

295
00:23:21,316 --> 00:23:25,343
Eight months later, goes up to a cabin,
middle of nowhere, dies cleaning his gun.

296
00:23:25,420 --> 00:23:29,652
So it's either two things.
He was dirty or it was a woman.

297
00:23:32,160 --> 00:23:33,149
What?

298
00:23:33,428 --> 00:23:35,828
I met him once, Milano.

299
00:23:36,264 --> 00:23:39,427
He had a poker up his ass,
but otherwise he was a good cop.

300
00:23:39,568 --> 00:23:42,264
- What I want to know is...
- I know what you want.

301
00:23:43,105 --> 00:23:44,504
I can't help you.

302
00:23:45,173 --> 00:23:46,435
Can't help me?

303
00:23:46,842 --> 00:23:47,934
Look...

304
00:23:49,010 --> 00:23:51,103
...do all of us a favor, okay?

305
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:53,341
Whatever you find out...

306
00:23:53,615 --> 00:23:55,207
...keep it to yourself.

307
00:23:59,621 --> 00:24:01,680
I got something for you.

308
00:24:02,057 --> 00:24:03,854
Documentary on Reese.

309
00:24:04,192 --> 00:24:06,683
Thank you. You're a real white man.

310
00:24:07,129 --> 00:24:08,289
Jonesy.

311
00:24:08,630 --> 00:24:11,656
- Tape on Reese. You want to view it?
- Give me a sec.

312
00:24:11,967 --> 00:24:13,764
What do you got on Muskavich?

313
00:24:13,835 --> 00:24:15,302
Fingerprints were bust.

314
00:24:15,370 --> 00:24:18,100
The crime scene says
the killer probably had dark hair.

315
00:24:18,173 --> 00:24:19,640
He probably was left-handed.

316
00:24:19,708 --> 00:24:21,300
Yeah, like Reese.

317
00:24:21,409 --> 00:24:24,207
He had bad teeth.
Found a piece in the corn flakes.

318
00:24:25,247 --> 00:24:26,509
<i>Directory Assistance.</i>

319
00:24:26,581 --> 00:24:28,776
Can you give me a number on a Milano...

320
00:24:28,884 --> 00:24:30,545
...Sylvia M-I-L-A-N-O.

321
00:24:30,652 --> 00:24:31,914
<i>Hold, please.</i>

322
00:24:31,987 --> 00:24:33,579
Hey, Lieutenant.

323
00:24:33,755 --> 00:24:35,222
Excuse me, boss.

324
00:24:38,326 --> 00:24:42,990
If somebody dies because you kept
your mouth shut, you're holding the bag.

325
00:24:43,165 --> 00:24:45,827
When it's a perfect world, let me know.

326
00:24:46,434 --> 00:24:49,665
In the meantime,
it's not me keeping his mouth shut.

327
00:24:50,238 --> 00:24:52,001
- Is that clear enough for you?
- Yeah.

328
00:24:52,240 --> 00:24:54,003
<i>I'm sorry. There's no listing.</i>

329
00:24:54,176 --> 00:24:57,577
Okay, thanks. No, listen, listen.
You still there? Hello?

330
00:24:57,746 --> 00:25:02,080
Check and see if there's a G. Milano,
a Gretta Milano. Can you do that for me?

331
00:25:02,250 --> 00:25:03,274
- <i>Hold, please.</i>
- Thanks.

332
00:25:03,385 --> 00:25:05,182
Syringe had the same prints.

333
00:25:07,189 --> 00:25:09,282
- So now what? Video time?
- Yeah.

334
00:25:11,359 --> 00:25:13,156
You know, I was thinking...

335
00:25:13,228 --> 00:25:14,627
Don't hurt yourself.

336
00:25:14,696 --> 00:25:15,685
Eat me.

337
00:25:15,830 --> 00:25:17,354
<i>Hold for the number.</i>

338
00:25:17,699 --> 00:25:20,691
Whoever did Muskavich,
knew the poison that Reese used.

339
00:25:20,869 --> 00:25:23,895
He quotes Reese. He could be a cop.

340
00:25:24,072 --> 00:25:25,699
He could be, huh?

341
00:25:25,874 --> 00:25:27,808
Lou, could be a cop, huh?

342
00:25:28,109 --> 00:25:30,202
<i>Please leave a message. Thank you.</i>

343
00:25:31,546 --> 00:25:33,776
<i>Make sure Hobbes gets a copy of this.</i>

344
00:25:34,049 --> 00:25:37,280
<i>You watching, Johnny-boy?</i>
<i>I hope you're paying close attention.</i>

345
00:25:37,886 --> 00:25:39,376
<i>Every gesture!</i>

346
00:25:39,621 --> 00:25:40,713
<i>Every word!</i>

347
00:25:49,564 --> 00:25:50,792
Wait a sec.

348
00:25:50,865 --> 00:25:51,957
What?

349
00:25:52,133 --> 00:25:53,623
Check something out.

350
00:26:00,075 --> 00:26:01,064
That...

351
00:26:01,409 --> 00:26:03,309
...language he was speaking...

352
00:26:03,511 --> 00:26:04,739
...later.

353
00:26:04,913 --> 00:26:06,312
That's Dutch?

354
00:26:07,249 --> 00:26:08,739
That's what he said.

355
00:26:09,317 --> 00:26:11,808
What's he speaking now? Is that Dutch?

356
00:26:12,921 --> 00:26:13,979
This now?

357
00:26:15,924 --> 00:26:18,188
This is mumbo-jumbo. Gibberish.

358
00:26:20,161 --> 00:26:21,594
You sure on that?

359
00:26:41,516 --> 00:26:42,778
<i>Who is it?</i>

360
00:26:42,884 --> 00:26:46,513
<i>It's detective John Hobbes.</i>
<i>I'm looking for Miss Gretta Milano.</i>

361
00:26:47,856 --> 00:26:50,290
- Oh, yes. You left a message.
- Yes.

362
00:26:51,126 --> 00:26:53,617
I wanted to talk to you about your father.

363
00:26:59,868 --> 00:27:01,233
How're you doing?

364
00:27:02,137 --> 00:27:03,365
May I come in?

365
00:27:05,640 --> 00:27:06,971
Sure.

366
00:27:16,885 --> 00:27:19,581
You're surrounded by angels.

367
00:27:20,322 --> 00:27:22,847
I teach theology at the university.

368
00:27:22,957 --> 00:27:25,323
I see. Very beautiful.

369
00:27:25,493 --> 00:27:26,653
Thank you.

370
00:27:27,495 --> 00:27:30,055
Why do you want to know
about my father?

371
00:27:32,901 --> 00:27:36,837
It's 30 years later and the files are sealed...

372
00:27:38,506 --> 00:27:41,532
...and my boss was told to let it alone, so...

373
00:27:42,510 --> 00:27:43,704
...here I am.

374
00:27:45,580 --> 00:27:48,845
I can tell you what my mother told me
before she died.

375
00:27:50,218 --> 00:27:52,846
Why do you want to know?
Just curious, or...?

376
00:27:52,954 --> 00:27:53,978
No, ma'am.

377
00:27:54,055 --> 00:27:57,354
See, I'm the detective
who caught Edgar Reese.

378
00:27:57,425 --> 00:28:00,292
I'm not sure if you're familiar with him.
He was just...

379
00:28:00,362 --> 00:28:02,296
- Yeah, I read about him.
- Right, right.

380
00:28:02,364 --> 00:28:05,026
And this Reese fella, he...

381
00:28:06,134 --> 00:28:08,864
...in a roundabout way,
gave me your father's name.

382
00:28:13,975 --> 00:28:15,567
Did Reese like to sing?

383
00:28:16,211 --> 00:28:17,838
Yeah, he did, actually.

384
00:28:19,881 --> 00:28:23,112
And at the execution,
did he try and touch you or grab you?

385
00:28:23,385 --> 00:28:25,785
Yeah, he did. He shook my hand.

386
00:28:27,789 --> 00:28:28,983
Want some coffee?

387
00:28:29,057 --> 00:28:30,217
Sure.

388
00:28:32,627 --> 00:28:34,117
Okay. One condition.

389
00:28:34,796 --> 00:28:36,388
You and I never spoke.

390
00:28:36,898 --> 00:28:40,629
You say nothing to your boss or partner.
Nothing goes in the files.

391
00:28:40,735 --> 00:28:44,296
My name and everything I say
is just between us. Agreed?

392
00:28:44,472 --> 00:28:46,337
Will I get coffee if I say yes?

393
00:28:49,978 --> 00:28:53,175
Detective, my dad was a good cop.

394
00:28:53,915 --> 00:28:57,407
Pride of the force and all that.
And then he shot himself.

395
00:28:57,585 --> 00:29:00,918
A reporter found out
my father had been under investigation.

396
00:29:00,989 --> 00:29:04,322
He'd caught a killer,
but copycat crimes started.

397
00:29:04,592 --> 00:29:07,823
Evidence mounted against him.
Fingerprints, witnesses.

398
00:29:07,962 --> 00:29:12,160
The press never got real proof,
but my father's medal was rescinded.

399
00:29:12,333 --> 00:29:13,425
I see.

400
00:29:13,835 --> 00:29:18,772
So you're saying that when he died
someone made this evidence go away?

401
00:29:19,274 --> 00:29:23,005
The mayor, governor and chief of police,
they all needed a hero.

402
00:29:23,111 --> 00:29:25,443
Some of these people are
still important today.

403
00:29:25,513 --> 00:29:28,107
- I see.
- No. Not yet, you don't.

404
00:29:28,850 --> 00:29:33,014
My father saw the evidence,
told my mother he couldn't beat it.

405
00:29:33,254 --> 00:29:35,745
So he went to this cabin in the mountains.

406
00:29:35,957 --> 00:29:39,188
It's a place that's been
in my mother's family for generations.

407
00:29:39,794 --> 00:29:41,284
He went there and...

408
00:29:45,533 --> 00:29:46,795
The thing is...

409
00:29:46,935 --> 00:29:49,699
...I know my father was innocent
of those murders.

410
00:29:50,472 --> 00:29:51,632
How do you know?

411
00:29:53,908 --> 00:29:55,466
How do you know he was innocent?

412
00:29:58,546 --> 00:30:01,174
It's 30 years ago.
It's not important anymore.

413
00:30:01,249 --> 00:30:03,410
It's important to me, Miss Milano.

414
00:30:03,485 --> 00:30:05,919
Don't you want the truth to come out,
the killer to be punished?

415
00:30:05,987 --> 00:30:08,285
- Of course, I do.
- But?

416
00:30:12,060 --> 00:30:15,894
Are you afraid if you tell me
your life may be in danger?

417
00:30:17,165 --> 00:30:18,223
Yeah.

418
00:30:18,399 --> 00:30:19,627
That's it?

419
00:30:20,502 --> 00:30:21,526
Yes.

420
00:30:23,238 --> 00:30:24,398
Okay.

421
00:30:27,175 --> 00:30:28,472
Okay.

422
00:30:28,543 --> 00:30:30,204
Thank you very much.

423
00:30:30,378 --> 00:30:32,505
- For the coffee as well.
- Okay.

424
00:30:35,650 --> 00:30:37,015
Oh, listen...

425
00:30:37,085 --> 00:30:39,417
If I have any more questions,
can I call you?

426
00:30:40,188 --> 00:30:41,553
I'd rather you didn't.

427
00:30:48,029 --> 00:30:49,587
Detective...

428
00:30:51,199 --> 00:30:52,496
Do you believe in God?

429
00:30:53,868 --> 00:30:56,132
Yeah. I go to church every now and then.

430
00:30:57,005 --> 00:30:58,905
What I see in my line of work...

431
00:30:59,307 --> 00:31:01,138
...faith's a little hard to sustain.

432
00:31:03,711 --> 00:31:04,769
Good luck.

433
00:31:13,488 --> 00:31:17,720
<i>Sometimes I think the basic job</i>
<i>that human beings have...</i>

434
00:31:17,892 --> 00:31:20,884
<i>... is just to figure out</i>
<i>what the hell is going on.</i>

435
00:31:21,062 --> 00:31:23,394
<i>Example: Gretta Milano.</i>

436
00:31:23,565 --> 00:31:27,057
<i>What was she hiding?</i>
<i>What was she so scared of?</i>

437
00:31:27,402 --> 00:31:31,133
<i>And then her question about God.</i>
<i>What the hell is that all about?</i>

438
00:31:39,047 --> 00:31:42,175
<i>You never know.</i>
<i>Down to the smallest thing.</i>

439
00:31:42,917 --> 00:31:46,683
<i>That man who passes you</i>
<i>and catches your eye. Does he know you?</i>

440
00:31:46,854 --> 00:31:51,257
<i>Did you go to school together? Is he a</i>
<i>homicidal maniac who hates you on sight?</i>

441
00:31:56,164 --> 00:31:57,495
<i>Or is it nothing?</i>

442
00:31:58,933 --> 00:32:00,195
<i>Nothing at all?</i>

443
00:32:48,816 --> 00:32:49,805
Wake up.

444
00:32:53,721 --> 00:32:55,780
Go to bed.

445
00:32:58,559 --> 00:33:00,584
I know. I know.

446
00:33:00,728 --> 00:33:02,662
Here we go. Up. Up.

447
00:33:02,830 --> 00:33:05,230
I'm going, Uncle John.

448
00:33:10,004 --> 00:33:11,096
Hello?

449
00:33:12,407 --> 00:33:13,533
Hello?

450
00:33:18,846 --> 00:33:20,074
Let's go, Sam.

451
00:33:30,091 --> 00:33:31,353
Good night.

452
00:33:31,526 --> 00:33:32,720
Good night, son.

453
00:33:37,598 --> 00:33:39,327
- Johnny?
- Yeah?

454
00:33:39,934 --> 00:33:41,401
You ever get scared?

455
00:33:43,871 --> 00:33:45,202
Yeah, sometimes.

456
00:33:49,877 --> 00:33:51,105
Me, too.

457
00:34:02,957 --> 00:34:04,117
Good night, Art.

458
00:34:25,480 --> 00:34:28,142
- <i>Hello?</i>
- Mrs. Moohr? This is Charles.

459
00:34:28,916 --> 00:34:31,407
Apparently I must have gotten drunk
or something...

460
00:34:31,486 --> 00:34:33,647
...because the last few days...

461
00:34:34,722 --> 00:34:36,019
Am I working tonight?

462
00:34:36,090 --> 00:34:37,352
<i>You quit.</i>

463
00:34:38,192 --> 00:34:39,250
I quit?

464
00:34:39,327 --> 00:34:42,592
<i>Yes. You insulted Harry</i>
<i>and he hired someone else.</i>

465
00:34:42,697 --> 00:34:44,756
But... I mean... How...?

466
00:34:48,369 --> 00:34:50,303
Look, I'm really sorry.

467
00:34:50,638 --> 00:34:53,937
Could you apologize, please,
to your husband for whatever...

468
00:34:54,008 --> 00:34:56,636
<i>We always liked you, Charles. Goodbye.</i>

469
00:35:17,799 --> 00:35:18,993
Hello?

470
00:35:23,304 --> 00:35:26,137
<i>Well, well, well. Look who's here.</i>

471
00:36:06,347 --> 00:36:09,612
I played Reese's tape on the phone
to a linguist. He's coming down.

472
00:36:09,684 --> 00:36:10,912
Yeah? Prelim?

473
00:36:10,985 --> 00:36:12,850
Said it sounded Mideastern.

474
00:36:13,087 --> 00:36:15,214
- Anything on Muskavich?
- Only the pizza.

475
00:36:15,289 --> 00:36:17,689
We're hitting your area of expertise, huh?

476
00:36:17,758 --> 00:36:19,749
Pizza is the staff of life.

477
00:36:20,094 --> 00:36:23,860
Without pizza and other fine Italian foods,
there would be no happiness.

478
00:36:24,265 --> 00:36:25,892
There was one slice left.

479
00:36:25,967 --> 00:36:28,527
Garlic, linguiça and pineapple.

480
00:36:28,903 --> 00:36:31,701
Plus there was nothing
in Muskavich's stomach.

481
00:36:31,873 --> 00:36:33,170
So it was the killer's eats.

482
00:36:33,241 --> 00:36:36,142
Hell of a clue. You better write
that one up for the journal.

483
00:36:36,210 --> 00:36:39,270
I will, Lou. And I will laud you copiously.

484
00:36:39,714 --> 00:36:40,703
Thank you.

485
00:36:40,815 --> 00:36:42,908
Detectives? Your guy's in video.

486
00:36:44,318 --> 00:36:45,979
The linguist guy's here.

487
00:36:46,621 --> 00:36:48,111
I'll be right there.

488
00:36:51,692 --> 00:36:52,716
Any luck?

489
00:36:52,860 --> 00:36:55,294
John Hobbes, Professor Richard Louders.

490
00:36:55,396 --> 00:36:57,091
- How do you do?
- Pleasure.

491
00:36:57,164 --> 00:36:59,155
This is completely exhilarating.

492
00:36:59,233 --> 00:37:01,565
Who is this convict? Can I speak to him?

493
00:37:01,969 --> 00:37:03,994
Not now. Have a seat.

494
00:37:04,338 --> 00:37:08,035
Professor says it's a language.
He's just never heard it spoken aloud.

495
00:37:08,109 --> 00:37:10,077
- Meaning?
- Some kind of antique.

496
00:37:10,244 --> 00:37:14,578
I believe this is a Biblical tongue.
Syrian Aramaic.

497
00:37:15,082 --> 00:37:17,346
Only a few nomadic tribes still use it.

498
00:37:17,418 --> 00:37:19,079
So you don't know what he's saying?

499
00:37:19,153 --> 00:37:20,643
Haven't the faintest.

500
00:37:20,988 --> 00:37:22,888
He's not too pleasant, is he?

501
00:37:24,258 --> 00:37:27,386
But if you'd spare me a copy,
I'd be more than happy to work it.

502
00:37:27,795 --> 00:37:31,629
Appreciate it. If you could wait
out front for 15 minutes...

503
00:37:31,933 --> 00:37:33,525
...we'll dupe one off for you.

504
00:37:33,601 --> 00:37:34,932
I'll be waiting.

505
00:37:35,336 --> 00:37:37,600
- See you in a minute.
- Bye, Detective.

506
00:37:43,444 --> 00:37:45,969
- Syrian Aramaic.
- Imagine that.

507
00:37:47,181 --> 00:37:50,378
I got something else, too.
I'm looking up this clipping...

508
00:37:50,518 --> 00:37:52,986
